The Ohlange High School holds a rich history, including being the first school in the country which was started by a black person, Dr John L Dube. The school was founded by Dube and his wife, Nokutela in the 1900s. Dube is considered as one of the founding fathers of democracy in SA and was also the first president of what was to be called the African National Congress. 
The second leg of the tour took delegates to Mahatma Gandhi House, Phoenix Settlement Durban. Museum in Bhambayi, Inanda.
The last and final part of the tour took delegates more than 100 kilometres out of the city to the Nelson Mandela Capture site in Howick. Here, delegates were educated about Mandela's last moments before he was arrested and incarcerated at Robben Island. 
